#let lesson = (
title: [RPC Flight Test]

,aim: [
Demonstrate all 16 flight elements, weight and balance, and full flight preparation to C standard before the CFI and be recommended for the issue of a Recreational Pilot Certificate.
]

,overview: [
The RPC Flight Test is conducted by the CFI, DCFI, or a designated Pilot Examiner (PE) authorised by RAAus under the Flight Operations Manual. The flight test is not a training event — it is a formal assessment of the candidate's ability to exercise the privileges of the RPC safely and independently. The examiner assesses against the syllabus C standard for all 16 elements, weight and balance competency, and the candidate's ability to plan and conduct a complete flight as pilot-in-command from the first action to the last.

This lesson plan is a reference document for both the examiner and the student. It does not contain new instruction — it documents the structure and requirements of the formal test.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
All 16 flight elements and weight and balance at C standard — as defined in each element's lesson plan and in the RAAus syllabus of flight training flight tolerance table.
]

,theory_knowledge: [
All theory exams confirmed passed before the test date. No new theory for this lesson.
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 60 minutes \
Equipment required: Student logbook, training record, all exam results, POH, NAIPS access, weight and balance worksheet, flight test paperwork \

*Final Pre-Test Administrative Gate* (15 minutes)

All of the following must be sighted and confirmed by the examiner before the flight test proceeds:

_Logbook:_
- ☐ Pilot logbook complete and up to date; all flights entered; all columns completed; all signatures present
- ☐ Total aeronautical experience: minimum 20 hours
- ☐ Solo PIC time: minimum 5 hours
- ☐ CFI endorsement in logbook confirming the student has met all training requirements and is recommended for flight test

_Theory exams — results sighted:_
- ☐ BAK: passed (minimum 80%, KDR completed)
- ☐ Air Legislation: passed (minimum 80%, KDR completed)
- ☐ Human Factors: passed (minimum 80%, KDR completed, or approved course)
- ☐ Radio: (minimum 80%, KDR completed)
- ☐ Weight and Balance: C standard confirmed in training record (L5.1)

_RAAus membership and currency:_
- ☐ Valid RAAus Student Pilot Certificate
- ☐ Financial flying membership current
- ☐ Health declaration current

_Training record:_
- ☐ All 16 flight elements recorded at C standard
- ☐ Practice flight test completed (L5.2); any NC items from practice test remediated (L5.3)
- ☐ Examiner confirms all documentation is complete before proceeding

*Test Brief* (60 minutes)
- Examiner confirms the flight test format: examiner role; no coaching; candidate plans and conducts the complete flight
- Candidate briefs the planned flight: weather, NOTAMs, weight and balance, EFATO plan
- Weight and balance calculation reviewed by examiner: correct calculation and within limits required before flight proceeds
- Examiner will ask oral theory questions during the ground brief
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Candidate*]
- Obtains NAIPS TAF/GAF/GPWT; checks BOM radar; briefs conditions and suitability
- Checks NOTAMs; briefs examiner on any relevant items
- Reviews maintenance release; briefs examiner on all items checked
- Calculates weight and balance for today's actual loading; plots CG on envelope; confirms within limits; briefs examiner
- Plans and briefs the complete flight: HASSELL minimum heights, EFATO plan, radio plan
- Delivers pre-takeoff safety brief

#text(size:12pt)[*Examiner*]
- Sights and confirms all administrative gate items before proceeding
- Receives candidate's full brief; will ask oral questions to assess depth of knowledge
- Does not provide any flight planning assistance, apart from telling the candidate the desired route; assesses the brief as presented
- Proceeds only when all gate items are confirmed
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Flight Test — Candidate as PIC, Examiner as Assessor*]
The examiner does not coach, prompt, or intervene except for safety. All assessment is silent.

The flight test covers all 16 elements in a logical, connected sequence as planned by the candidate. The examiner may request specific elements or sequences during the flight. At minimum the following must be demonstrated:

- E1: Pre-flight preparation and ground operations — planning, documentation, pre-flight inspection
- E2: Effects of controls — demonstrated en route or by specific exercise as required
- E3: Straight and level — cruise and slow cruise; heading ±5°, altitude ±150 ft
- E4: Climbing — Vy; heading ±5°, airspeed +10/−0 kts; correct level-off
- E5: Descending — at least two descent profiles; correct level-off
- E6: Basic turning — 15° and 30° AoB; altitude ±150 ft; rollout ±10°
- E7: Slow flight and stall recognition — pre-stall symptoms identified; HASSELL; correct recovery
- E8: Take off — pre-takeoff brief; directional control; Vy established; after-takeoff checks
- E9: Advanced turning — 60° AoB; altitude ±100 ft; rollout ±10°; spiral dive recovery if requested
- E10: Scenario based stalling — at least two scenarios; HASSELL; correct recovery; height loss ≤300 ft
- E11: Circuits and circuit emergencies — normal circuit; EFATO simulation; flapless approach
- E12: Landing — normal powered approach; stable approach gate; correct hold-off; touchdown ±30 m
- E13: Avionics and communications — all calls correct; active listening; transponder; radio failure if tested
- E14: Forced landing — ABCDEF sequence from memory; FLWOP circuit; MAYDAY simulated
- E15: Training area operations — circuit departure; area operations; overhead join; airspace awareness
- E16: Unusual attitudes and emergencies — one nose-high, one nose-low; correct recovery sequence
- Weight and balance: demonstrated during pre-flight planning

#text(size:12pt)[*Examiner*]
- Records C or NC for each element
- Intervenes only for safety
- If a safety issue requires intervention — notes it; assesses whether the candidate's actions would have resolved the situation independently
- Automatic NC for any control intervention
]

,common_errors:[
Not applicable — this is a formal assessment, not an instructional lesson.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Examiner Debrief* (20 min):
  - Reports C or NC for each element with specific evidence
  - If all elements at C standard: recommends candidate for RPC; completes RAAus flight test paperwork; signs logbook
  - If one or more elements NC: explains what was observed; does not recommend; candidate must remediate and rebook with CFI
  - Provides verbal acknowledgement of the candidate's demonstrated strengths

- *If recommended:*
  - Examiner completes and signs RAAus flight test result form
  - Candidate's logbook endorsed with RPC recommendation
  - RAAus membership updated; RPC issued per RAAus FOM process
  - CFI notified and training file closed

- *If not recommended:*
  - NC elements clearly recorded with evidence
  - Remediation plan agreed with candidate and CFI
  - Flight test may be rebooked with CFI after targeted remediation
]

,standards_for_progression:[
*Flight test pass requirements — all must be met:*

_Administrative gate (confirmed before test proceeds):_
- ☐ Logbook complete; minimum 20 hours total; minimum 5 hours solo PIC
- ☐ CFI endorsement for flight test in logbook
- ☐ BAK, Air Legislation, Human Factors passed and recorded
- ☐ Radio Operator recorded
- ☐ Weight and Balance at C standard
- ☐ All 16 elements at C standard in training record
- ☐ RAAus Student Pilot Certificate, membership, and health declaration current

_In-flight assessment:_
- All 16 elements demonstrated to C standard per the RAAus syllabus of flight training/FIRM flight tolerance table
- Weight and balance calculated correctly and within limits before flight
- Flight planned and conducted independently; no coaching from examiner

*RPC is issued when all administrative and in-flight requirements are met.*

- *Outcome*: Flight test result recorded on RAAus form and in student training record. RPC issued or remediation plan agreed.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: All element-specific minima apply; examiner confirms conditions are suitable before the test proceeds; if conditions deteriorate during the test — examiner may terminate and reschedule
- *Examiner authority*: The examiner has full authority to terminate the flight test at any time for safety reasons; a termination for safety does not automatically result in a fail — the examiner assesses whether the safety issue was caused by the candidate or by external factors
- *TEM*:
  - Flight test anxiety is normal; the examiner should establish a calm, professional tone during the ground brief
  - If the candidate appears significantly distressed before the flight — the examiner may defer the test; a distressed candidate is unlikely to demonstrate their true capability
  - All emergency simulations (EFATO, ABCDEF) are clearly briefed before the flight; the examiner confirms the candidate's understanding before initiating any simulation
]

,homework:[
No homework — this is the final assessment. After the flight test:
- If recommended: register with RAAus; obtain RPC; review the conditions and limitations of the certificate
- If not recommended: review the specific NC items; schedule remediation with the CFI; approach the retest with a clear understanding of what specifically needs to be different
]
)

